In her speech at the White House, the First Lady expressed her admiration for the disability community and their resilience. She highlighted the activism of individuals like Jennifer Keelan-Chaffins, who crawled up the Congressional steps to raise awareness about the lack of accessibility. The First Lady credited the efforts of these activists for the passing of the Americans with Disabilities Act 32 years ago. She also acknowledged the ongoing contributions of the disability community in shaping the nation, from crafting laws to pushing the boundaries of the future. The First Lady, who is an English teacher herself, shared a quote from advocate and poet Susan Mazrui, emphasizing the community's role as problem solvers and their commitment to fighting inequity. She concluded by celebrating their power and pride and introduced Mayor Tim Adams, who is working towards further progress.